WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:03.000
Baltimore, Baltimore, Baltimore.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:09.500
So, ladies and gentlemen, some of you may know Jeff from online

00:00:09.500 --> 00:00:14.500
courses. I'm going to hand over to him. Please, a warm round of

00:00:14.500 --> 00:00:16.500
applause.

00:00:20.500 --> 00:00:22.500
I'm super excited to be here. This is my very first RStudio

00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:24.500
conf. Thank you so much for the invite. I'm going to talk about

00:00:24.500 --> 00:00:26.500
a project we've been doing in Baltimore to use data science to

00:00:26.500 --> 00:00:28.500
create new economic opportunities.

00:00:28.500 --> 00:00:30.500
We rely heavily on tools developed by RStudio, so I'm

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:32.500
really grateful for all the help they've helped us do over the

00:00:32.500 --> 00:00:34.500
last couple of years. I talk super fast, so you're going to

00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:36.500
see a lot of slides. If you want to follow along or look at them

00:00:36.500 --> 00:00:38.500
later, you can find them at this website.

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:40.500
So, first, I wanted to thank a lot of people who took a gamble

00:00:40.500 --> 00:00:42.500
on this project, and in particular, I really wanted to

00:00:42.500 --> 00:00:44.500
thank four people, Shannon Ellis, Abuzar Ahadavan, Jamie

00:00:44.500 --> 00:00:46.500
McGovern, and Ashley Johnson, who I had this completely

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:48.500
harebrained idea to do this project, and they all gambled on

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:50.500
it. So, thank you to all of them.

00:00:50.500 --> 00:00:52.500
I'm going to turn it over to them.

00:00:52.500 --> 00:00:54.500
Thank you.

00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:00.500
So, I'm going to turn it over to the other people who gambled

00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:02.500
on me with the project, and I really appreciate their time,

00:01:02.500 --> 00:01:04.500
and then you'll hear about some of the other people that have

00:01:04.500 --> 00:01:06.500
gambled on us, and hopefully it's paid off for them.

00:01:06.500 --> 00:01:08.500
So, they're the real MVPs of the talk that I am giving to here.

00:01:08.500 --> 00:01:10.500
I'm just the mouthpiece.

00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:12.500
So, this whole project has felt a lot like this.

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:14.500
This is a project, I'll tell you, that has a lot of moving

00:01:14.500 --> 00:01:16.500
parts, and it's felt like, you know, throughout the project,

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:18.500
we're a train going down a track, and we're rapidly trying

00:01:18.500 --> 00:01:20.500
to get debris off the track so that we don't go off.

00:01:20.500 --> 00:01:22.500
And all the people that I just showed you a minute ago are

00:01:22.500 --> 00:01:24.500
people that helped us solve problems.

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:26.500
So, we're going to talk a little bit about the project.

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:29.500
So, as you probably heard or know, or you've read about in

00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:31.500
the news recently, income inequality is a big problem in

00:01:31.500 --> 00:01:33.500
the world.

00:01:33.500 --> 00:01:35.500
And I work in a school of public health, and it turns out

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:37.500
income inequality is also a public health problem.

00:01:37.500 --> 00:01:39.500
If you look, this is actual real data.

00:01:39.500 --> 00:01:41.500
I know the line is so straight, it looks like I made it up.

00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:43.500
This is real data.

00:01:43.500 --> 00:01:45.500
It is the relationship between how much money you make and

00:01:45.500 --> 00:01:47.500
what your life expectancy is based on census records for the

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:49.500
entire United States.

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:51.500
If you make, at the 80th anniversary of the Great Depression,

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:53.500
if you make $10,000 a year, if you make $10,000 a year,

00:01:53.500 --> 00:01:55.500
if you make $10,000 a year, if you make $10,000 a year,

00:01:55.500 --> 00:01:57.500
if you make, at the 80th percentile, on average,

00:01:57.500 --> 00:01:59.500
you live between five and seven years longer than people who

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:01.500
make at the 20th percentile.

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:03.500
This is a correlation, of course, not causation,

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:05.500
but this is an incredibly tight correlation,

00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:07.500
and it also relates to every other public health consequence

00:02:07.500 --> 00:02:09.500
that you might imagine.

00:02:09.500 --> 00:02:11.500
So, at the same time that economic inequality could cause

00:02:11.500 --> 00:02:13.500
some concern for us about public health differences and

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:15.500
disparities, economic mobility is also at a record low.

00:02:15.500 --> 00:02:17.500
So, this is a map produced by the Harvard group,

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:19.500
and it's a map of the population.

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:21.500
So, this is a map of the population,

00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:23.500
and it's a map of the population.

00:02:23.500 --> 00:02:25.500
So, this is a map produced by the Harvard group,

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:27.500
Raj Chetty's group, looking at economic mobility

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:29.500
in the United States.

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:31.500
And this is the neighborhood around where I work

00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:33.500
at Johns Hopkins.

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:35.500
Johns Hopkins is a massive, multibillion-dollar institution

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:37.500
with a lot of very well-paid doctors,

00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:39.500
but the median income for a person that grows up in the

00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:41.500
neighborhood around our hospital is $18,000 for a family

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:43.500
at the age of 34.

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:45.500
So, that, and not only that, but the chance of going from

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:47.500
that income to going up to a higher level of income

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:49.500
is very small.

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:51.500
This isn't just a problem in cities.

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:53.500
This is, I grew up in Pocatello, Idaho,

00:02:53.500 --> 00:02:55.500
which is a random little town in Idaho,

00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:57.500
and there's a similar, hey, there's some Pocatellans,

00:02:57.500 --> 00:02:59.500
find me later.

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:01.500
So, and this is a similar kind of economic mobility

00:03:01.500 --> 00:03:03.500
challenge, even in rural parts of the United States.

00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:05.500
It turns out that the best way to solve the economic

00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:07.500
mobility problem, the best intervention anybody's ever

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:09.500
invented is education, but it turns out that you need

00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:11.500
access to education in order to be able to take advantage

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:13.500
of this intervention.

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:15.500
So, if you see a plot on the x-axis,

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:17.500
how easy it is to get into a university,

00:03:17.500 --> 00:03:19.500
and on the y-axis, how easy it is to get into a

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:21.500
university, and on the y-axis, how likely it is

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:23.500
you'll be in the 80th percentile or above

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:25.500
of income after you finish, you see that there's

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:27.500
this kind of L shape.

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:29.500
The easier it is to get into, the less money you make

00:03:29.500 --> 00:03:31.500
when you get out.

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:33.500
The harder it is to get into, the more money you'll

00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:35.500
make when you get out.

00:03:35.500 --> 00:03:37.500
Technical education obviously breaks this trend

00:03:37.500 --> 00:03:39.500
and gives us an opportunity to inexpensive education

00:03:39.500 --> 00:03:41.500
and move people up the economic mobility ladder.

00:03:41.500 --> 00:03:43.500
This whole project is predicated on the hypothesis

00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:45.500
that talent is evenly distributed,

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:47.500
but opportunity isn't.

00:03:47.500 --> 00:03:49.500
So, we've been teaching data science online

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:51.500
for a little while now.

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:53.500
We've taught more than 5 million people

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:55.500
on the Coursera platform in just straight data science

00:03:55.500 --> 00:03:57.500
using R.

00:03:57.500 --> 00:03:59.500
We've also taught 6 million plus across a variety

00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:01.500
of different data science modalities,

00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:03.500
and so that's something we're really excited about

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:05.500
and we're really proud of.

00:04:05.500 --> 00:04:07.500
But one thing that we wanted to know is,

00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:09.500
could people use these programs to improve

00:04:09.500 --> 00:04:11.500
their economic prospects?

00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:13.500
So, we did a study, and we looked at what people's

00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:15.500
income was before they took our program and after,

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:17.500
and the dots, which you probably can't see too well,

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:19.500
but are up in this top left-hand corner,

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:21.500
are people who had below-poverty-level income

00:04:21.500 --> 00:04:23.500
but ended up at above the 80th percentile of income

00:04:23.500 --> 00:04:25.500
after taking a $1,000 online program

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:27.500
that they took in their spare time.

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:29.500
That was a very, very small subset

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:31.500
of our Coursera students,

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:33.500
but it's a pretty inspiring subset of those Coursera students.

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:35.500
So, it turns out, though, that almost everybody

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:37.500
that takes our Coursera classes

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:39.500
are already educated.

00:04:39.500 --> 00:04:41.500
You know, the most common user

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:43.500
of one of our Coursera classes is an upper-middle-class

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:45.500
white male Silicon Valley engineer,

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:47.500
so there's probably a few around here,

00:04:47.500 --> 00:04:49.500
which is great, and we love educating those folks,

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:51.500
but it's not reaching the broad audience.

00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:53.500
So, even if you build it,

00:04:53.500 --> 00:04:55.500
they won't necessarily come to the massive online open courses.

00:04:55.500 --> 00:04:57.500
So, we started thinking about,

00:04:57.500 --> 00:04:59.500
from first principles, how do we take somebody

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:01.500
who's maybe never heard of data science

00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:03.500
and turn them into a functioning data scientist

00:05:03.500 --> 00:05:05.500
who can get a job and improve their economic prospects?

00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:07.500
So, these are the challenges that we came up with.

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:09.500
Shannon and Abuzar and Sean,

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:11.500
who's sitting here in the front,

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:13.500
got back in my office a few years ago.

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:15.500
And so, we thought

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:17.500
an expensive computer is a challenge.

00:05:17.500 --> 00:05:19.500
It's been said that a data scientist

00:05:19.500 --> 00:05:21.500
is a statistician working on a MacBook Pro.

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:23.500
That'll run you about $3,000

00:05:23.500 --> 00:05:25.500
for a MacBook Pro, but if your income last year

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:27.500
as a family was $5,000,

00:05:27.500 --> 00:05:29.500
you're not buying a MacBook Pro.

00:05:29.500 --> 00:05:31.500
So, we wanted to build a program that could be run on any computer

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:33.500
that has an internet connection and a web browser.

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:35.500
So, this is where we relied heavily.

00:05:35.500 --> 00:05:37.500
We were the initial beta testers.

00:05:37.500 --> 00:05:39.500
Tarif and Robby helped us out a lot,

00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:41.500
got us on RStudio Cloud, helped us scale this whole program.

00:05:41.500 --> 00:05:43.500
That was the only way we would be able to do that.

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:45.500
So, we've been doing data science

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:47.500
on a Chromebook for a while.

00:05:47.500 --> 00:05:49.500
You can do it with Google Slides, Google Sheets,

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:51.500
but the real hero of this story in terms of technology

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:53.500
is RStudio Cloud.

00:05:53.500 --> 00:05:55.500
So, we ran our whole new MOOC sequence.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:57.500
We built an entirely new MOOC sequence

00:05:57.500 --> 00:05:59.500
entirely based on RStudio Cloud

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:01.500
so that anybody could take it.

00:06:01.500 --> 00:06:03.500
You could go to the public library

00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:05.500
and take our data science series on the web browser.

00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:07.500
Then you'd have to know about data science.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:09.500
I've talked to a lot of the people in the community

00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:11.500
where we have run this program.

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:13.500
They've never heard of that.

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:15.500
They don't know it's a thing.

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:17.500
They don't know you could do something with it.

00:06:17.500 --> 00:06:19.500
They don't know you could improve your life with it.

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:21.500
So, we had to tell people about that,

00:06:21.500 --> 00:06:23.500
and again, this is the same problem we had before.

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:25.500
Most people who are taking these online courses

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:27.500
are already educated, so they hear about data science.

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:29.500
This is not exclusive to us.

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:31.500
If you've heard of a data science boot camp

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:33.500
or Lambda School or any of these other things,

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:35.500
if you look at the data on who's being educated

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:37.500
among already educated folks.

00:06:37.500 --> 00:06:39.500
So, we went out and partnered

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:41.500
with a nonprofit in East Baltimore

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:43.500
just off the block where we work,

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:45.500
Historic East Baltimore Community Action Coalition,

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:47.500
and so they're amazing,

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:49.500
and they have a GED training program,

00:06:49.500 --> 00:06:51.500
and so they also have access to a catchment area

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:53.500
of a lot of really talented youth

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:55.500
who maybe had not heard about data science.

00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:57.500
So, we worked with them to identify some people

00:06:57.500 --> 00:06:59.500
and to tell them about data science.

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:01.500
Then we needed an appropriate program.

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:03.500
So, the cool thing about the tools

00:07:03.500 --> 00:07:05.500
that have been built by R

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:07.500
is that with a relatively little amount of overhead,

00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:09.500
you can go from nothing to magic,

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:11.500
and so we can compress training programs

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:13.500
that make people very capable

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:15.500
down into very short periods of time.

00:07:15.500 --> 00:07:17.500
With this much code,

00:07:17.500 --> 00:07:19.500
you can build a funny little website.

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:21.500
With this much code,

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:23.500
you can build an interactive dashboard

00:07:23.500 --> 00:07:25.500
on the NHANES data.

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:27.500
With this much code,

00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:29.500
you can access a gigantic database

00:07:29.500 --> 00:07:31.500
and process thousands and thousands

00:07:31.500 --> 00:07:33.500
and you can scrape data

00:07:33.500 --> 00:07:35.500
or connect to APIs,

00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:37.500
all of the things that the packages have been.

00:07:37.500 --> 00:07:39.500
We've been early adopters of all of them.

00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:41.500
So, we built a program called Cloud-Based Data Science.

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:43.500
Anybody can take it.

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:45.500
It's online, it's free.

00:07:45.500 --> 00:07:47.500
Go to clouddatascience.org.

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:49.500
We have tons of people taking it all over the world,

00:07:49.500 --> 00:07:51.500
but we also partnered

00:07:51.500 --> 00:07:53.500
with this nonprofit

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:55.500
to run the program locally in Baltimore.

00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:57.500
So, we had our content development

00:07:57.500 --> 00:07:59.500
starting in February 2018.

00:07:59.500 --> 00:08:01.500
We had our first meeting with Yode,

00:08:01.500 --> 00:08:03.500
the Hebcax training program.

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:05.500
They said, hey, this is great.

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:07.500
We should start tomorrow.

00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:09.500
We had started content development on February 2018,

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:11.500
so we said, maybe next month?

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:13.500
And they said, okay, May 21st it is.

00:08:13.500 --> 00:08:15.500
So, remember,

00:08:15.500 --> 00:08:17.500
I had to build a whole training program

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:19.500
and we had a month to do it.

00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:21.500
So, this was me

00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:23.500
in my office after that meeting

00:08:23.500 --> 00:08:25.500
trying to figure out how we would do it.

00:08:25.500 --> 00:08:27.500
Fortunately, we had this amazing team

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:29.500
of people who developed content

00:08:29.500 --> 00:08:31.500
for us in a distributed way,

00:08:31.500 --> 00:08:33.500
and Shannon Ellis and Abuzar Hadavan

00:08:33.500 --> 00:08:35.500
deserve the lion's share of the credit

00:08:35.500 --> 00:08:37.500
in terms of content development,

00:08:37.500 --> 00:08:39.500
but what was amazing is we actually had

00:08:39.500 --> 00:08:41.500
technologies developed by Sean Cross

00:08:41.500 --> 00:08:43.500
and by John Muschelli that allowed us

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:45.500
to develop and deploy this content very quickly.

00:08:45.500 --> 00:08:47.500
So, then we've solved a couple of the problems,

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:49.500
but there are still some problems out there.

00:08:49.500 --> 00:08:51.500
We still got to get them a computer,

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:53.500
access to instruction, income security.

00:08:53.500 --> 00:08:55.500
So, we have developed

00:08:55.500 --> 00:08:57.500
this training program

00:08:57.500 --> 00:08:59.500
and we wanted to be able to do it very quickly

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:01.500
so that we could give them this kind of access.

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:03.500
This is a GitHub repo

00:09:03.500 --> 00:09:05.500
that is the 34,000 repos

00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:07.500
of our Getting and Cleaning Data final projects

00:09:07.500 --> 00:09:09.500
for our Coursera class.

00:09:09.500 --> 00:09:11.500
You can go online and see all the 34,000 projects

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:13.500
people have done.

00:09:13.500 --> 00:09:15.500
If you look at what libraries were used

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:17.500
in the development of this course,

00:09:17.500 --> 00:09:19.500
you'll notice there was a strong trend

00:09:19.500 --> 00:09:21.500
for one package. It's the dplyr package.

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:23.500
This package was released the day

00:09:23.500 --> 00:09:25.500
I released my Getting and Cleaning Data course

00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:27.500
and rendered the entire course obsolete

00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:29.500
on Coursera on day one.

00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:31.500
Thanks, Hadley, very much.

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:33.500
Appreciate that.

00:09:33.500 --> 00:09:35.500
So, we learned our lesson, and first,

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:37.500
we monitor everything that our studio people

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:39.500
are doing at all times while we're building courses.

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:41.500
But second, Sean built

00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:43.500
some really awesome technologies that allowed us

00:09:43.500 --> 00:09:45.500
to automatically synthesize the voices

00:09:45.500 --> 00:09:47.500
around our videos and automatically generate

00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:49.500
all of our videos and all of our MOOCs

00:09:49.500 --> 00:09:51.500
from our Markdown documents and from Google Slides.

00:09:51.500 --> 00:09:53.500
So we can recompile and re-release

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:55.500
new courses very, very rapidly

00:09:55.500 --> 00:09:57.500
to be able to deploy this program.

00:09:57.500 --> 00:09:59.500
Similarly, all of our tutorials are built

00:09:59.500 --> 00:10:01.500
in an amazing program called Swirl,

00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:03.500
also developed by Sean and Nick Carcetti,

00:10:03.500 --> 00:10:05.500
who I don't think is here,

00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:07.500
that allows us to write sort of Markdown-like,

00:10:07.500 --> 00:10:09.500
YAML-like tutorials that people

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:11.500
can then interactively take in R.

00:10:11.500 --> 00:10:13.500
So, we wanted to go after this new cohort

00:10:13.500 --> 00:10:15.500
which comes from a different sort of

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:17.500
level of education and from a different background,

00:10:17.500 --> 00:10:19.500
so we built a training program

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:21.500
that has in-person office hours

00:10:21.500 --> 00:10:23.500
three hours a week, you get paid to complete

00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:25.500
the courses, you get a free Chromebook,

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:27.500
and then we help you with job assistance.

00:10:27.500 --> 00:10:29.500
I get up very, very early in the morning

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:31.500
because I have young kids and my post-doc goes to sleep

00:10:31.500 --> 00:10:33.500
very, very late because he doesn't have young kids,

00:10:33.500 --> 00:10:35.500
and so you get basically 24-hour Slack support

00:10:35.500 --> 00:10:37.500
when you're taking our courses.

00:10:37.500 --> 00:10:39.500
And then we partnered with

00:10:39.500 --> 00:10:41.500
EO and they provided

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:43.500
the real work, which is like

00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:45.500
wraparound services, housing support, things like that

00:10:45.500 --> 00:10:47.500
for people who needed it.

00:10:47.500 --> 00:10:49.500
And then we decided to run a pilot, so we ran it with

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:51.500
I was going to run it with 20 people, and Joe Chang came

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:53.500
to visit us in Baltimore and he said

00:10:53.500 --> 00:10:55.500
that is a terrible idea, try two first.

00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:57.500
So we did, we tried it with two people.

00:10:57.500 --> 00:10:59.500
The learning started May 21st.

00:10:59.500 --> 00:11:01.500
How long should the program take?

00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:03.500
We don't know, we just made this up last week.

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:05.500
So, we said three months,

00:11:05.500 --> 00:11:07.500
which is a dramatically short

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:09.500
timeline to learn a lot of data science,

00:11:09.500 --> 00:11:11.500
especially for people who had never

00:11:11.500 --> 00:11:13.500
heard of data science and were already looking at us

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:15.500
a little skeptically to start.

00:11:15.500 --> 00:11:17.500
Surprisingly, even with these challenges

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:19.500
of us basically being behind in content

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:21.500
development, both of the candidates

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:23.500
finished the program in four months.

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:25.500
The new cohorts have finished in the three

00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:27.500
months we originally projected, because now

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:29.500
content is done instead of

00:11:29.500 --> 00:11:31.500
the first cohort where they weren't.

00:11:31.500 --> 00:11:33.500
So we've had multiple cohorts go through this

00:11:33.500 --> 00:11:35.500
and we've had an 80% success rate.

00:11:35.500 --> 00:11:37.500
This is an incredible success

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:39.500
rate, given that the people that we're working with

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:41.500
had never heard about data science beforehand

00:11:41.500 --> 00:11:43.500
and it's really a testament to

00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:45.500
the incredibly talented people that we're

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:47.500
working with who just didn't have an opportunity to do

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:49.500
this, and now they pick

00:11:49.500 --> 00:11:51.500
it up way faster. They're teaching

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:53.500
me stuff now.

00:11:53.500 --> 00:11:55.500
The next challenge that we had is

00:11:55.500 --> 00:11:57.500
we wanted to use this as an economic

00:11:57.500 --> 00:11:59.500
intervention, but if you've ever seen a job ad

00:11:59.500 --> 00:12:01.500
for a data scientist, these are your actual

00:12:01.500 --> 00:12:03.500
roles and responsibilities,

00:12:03.500 --> 00:12:05.500
but these are the job requirements.

00:12:05.500 --> 00:12:07.500
And so,

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:09.500
that's a bit of a problem when we're

00:12:09.500 --> 00:12:11.500
training people to do really powerful,

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:13.500
useful stuff, but the job requirements look like that.

00:12:13.500 --> 00:12:15.500
It's true

00:12:15.500 --> 00:12:17.500
for this, as I'm picking on someone in particular in the

00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:19.500
Baltimore area, but this is, you know, you need a

00:12:19.500 --> 00:12:21.500
bachelor's degree and five years of experience, and what they really

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:23.500
needed was somebody to look into their SQL databases

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:25.500
and figure out what was going on.

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:27.500
So, it turns out there's a problem

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:29.500
with us directly employing the data scientists

00:12:29.500 --> 00:12:31.500
we've trained if they don't have a bachelor's degree.

00:12:31.500 --> 00:12:33.500
One of the people that's completed our program

00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:35.500
has had a bachelor's degree. He's actually

00:12:35.500 --> 00:12:37.500
here today somewhere. There he is.

00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:39.500
Anthony. You should go talk to him later.

00:12:39.500 --> 00:12:41.500
And Antonio, who's also

00:12:41.500 --> 00:12:43.500
here, completed our program,

00:12:43.500 --> 00:12:45.500
is getting his bachelor's degree, and he's going to be a doctor

00:12:45.500 --> 00:12:47.500
someday as fast as he possibly can.

00:12:47.500 --> 00:12:49.500
But the Fair Labor and Standards Act

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:51.500
doesn't, you know, have these carve-outs

00:12:51.500 --> 00:12:53.500
for who can be a salaried employee.

00:12:53.500 --> 00:12:55.500
I learned a lot about HR law

00:12:55.500 --> 00:12:57.500
through this project, and it turns out

00:12:57.500 --> 00:12:59.500
data scientists doesn't meet the software engineering

00:12:59.500 --> 00:13:01.500
requirement for the Fair Labor and Standards Act

00:13:01.500 --> 00:13:03.500
to be an exempt employee.

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:05.500
I've talked to a lot of lawyers about this.

00:13:05.500 --> 00:13:07.500
So, this is a problem because now

00:13:07.500 --> 00:13:09.500
you have to hire the folks that we've trained

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:11.500
as hourly employees.

00:13:11.500 --> 00:13:13.500
So I was this close. I've trained incredibly

00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:15.500
talented people who are super smart, can do

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:17.500
incredible things, but

00:13:17.500 --> 00:13:19.500
they don't have a job that they can

00:13:19.500 --> 00:13:21.500
get because the labor laws require

00:13:21.500 --> 00:13:23.500
them to be an hourly job, but they're being listed

00:13:23.500 --> 00:13:25.500
as salary jobs, and so I'm in a

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:27.500
bit of a pickle. I work at

00:13:27.500 --> 00:13:29.500
Hopkins, and I'm a faculty member, and

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:31.500
when you're a faculty member at a place like Hopkins, you can

00:13:31.500 --> 00:13:33.500
pitch a fit and try to get them to do things for you.

00:13:33.500 --> 00:13:35.500
And so I did that, and I have

00:13:35.500 --> 00:13:37.500
over the last year and a half pitched enough fits

00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:39.500
that they've created a new job classification

00:13:39.500 --> 00:13:41.500
just last week so that people

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:43.500
that complete our training program can be employed

00:13:43.500 --> 00:13:45.500
at Johns Hopkins as data scientists, so

00:13:45.500 --> 00:13:47.500
very excited about that.

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:49.500
But that was, thank you very much.

00:13:49.500 --> 00:13:51.500
Yeah, I feel like I should get the applause

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:53.500
for battling the HR system and winning.

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:55.500
So, but

00:13:55.500 --> 00:13:57.500
in the meantime, we didn't have a place for people

00:13:57.500 --> 00:13:59.500
to be employed even though they're super talented.

00:13:59.500 --> 00:14:01.500
Well, it turns out a lot of people were emailing me to do data science

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:03.500
consulting work because I'm on Coursera all the time,

00:14:03.500 --> 00:14:05.500
and I used to just hit delete on all those emails,

00:14:05.500 --> 00:14:07.500
sorry, but then

00:14:07.500 --> 00:14:09.500
I had an amazing outreach from

00:14:09.500 --> 00:14:11.500
some folks at, this guy's

00:14:11.500 --> 00:14:13.500
from Wyden Kennedy, and he said,

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:15.500
hey, right at the time when I was launching this, he

00:14:15.500 --> 00:14:17.500
said, hey, do you want to do some stuff together?

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:19.500
A couple of the people from WK might be here

00:14:19.500 --> 00:14:21.500
who we work with a lot. They're amazing.

00:14:21.500 --> 00:14:23.500
And they, we, so we've started to work

00:14:23.500 --> 00:14:25.500
with companies like that and to basically do

00:14:25.500 --> 00:14:27.500
data science as a service for them.

00:14:27.500 --> 00:14:29.500
And so what we found in doing that is

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:31.500
with a lot of companies, WK is one

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:33.500
of the best case scenarios.

00:14:33.500 --> 00:14:35.500
In a lot of the cases we work with companies,

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:37.500
the main problem is the data isn't organized.

00:14:37.500 --> 00:14:39.500
As everyone knows, 80% of the problem is data cleaning.

00:14:39.500 --> 00:14:41.500
So we've kind of

00:14:41.500 --> 00:14:43.500
created a product which is

00:14:43.500 --> 00:14:45.500
tidy data as a service. We call it

00:14:45.500 --> 00:14:47.500
Streamline, but the idea is

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:49.500
basically we go in and build a custom set of pipelines

00:14:49.500 --> 00:14:51.500
that pull everybody's data in, put it in a database

00:14:51.500 --> 00:14:53.500
every night, and so they have the clean

00:14:53.500 --> 00:14:55.500
data that they need to use. And so

00:14:55.500 --> 00:14:57.500
we've been deploying this,

00:14:57.500 --> 00:14:59.500
the team, you should meet Antonio and Anthony

00:14:59.500 --> 00:15:01.500
back, they're super talented. Hire them away

00:15:01.500 --> 00:15:03.500
from us, please, and then I'll train more.

00:15:03.500 --> 00:15:05.500
And so we founded

00:15:05.500 --> 00:15:07.500
this company and we decided we were going to put it right

00:15:07.500 --> 00:15:09.500
in the neighborhood where this is happening. So our company

00:15:09.500 --> 00:15:11.500
is headquartered like right up the block from Hopkins.

00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:13.500
We're hiring data scientists from this training

00:15:13.500 --> 00:15:15.500
program, and we think of that as their first

00:15:15.500 --> 00:15:17.500
data science opportunity, but they're so talented

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:19.500
that's definitely not going to be their last data science

00:15:19.500 --> 00:15:21.500
opportunity. So this

00:15:21.500 --> 00:15:23.500
is the project we set out to try to accomplish.

00:15:23.500 --> 00:15:25.500
We've tackled each

00:15:25.500 --> 00:15:27.500
of this bit by bit. It's still a little bit

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:29.500
held together with sticks and mud and glue

00:15:29.500 --> 00:15:31.500
and the hard work of Anthony and Antonio and their

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:33.500
friends, but

00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:35.500
we're taking a big swing at

00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:37.500
how do we tackle getting RStudio

00:15:37.500 --> 00:15:39.500
and R and these sort of talents, just like

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:41.500
Carl mentioned, how do we use this as an

00:15:41.500 --> 00:15:43.500
engine to create economic opportunities

00:15:43.500 --> 00:15:45.500
for people who wouldn't otherwise have them in this area

00:15:45.500 --> 00:15:47.500
and tackle these big public health problems

00:15:47.500 --> 00:15:49.500
head on. So

00:15:49.500 --> 00:15:51.500
if you want to read more about this, again,

00:15:51.500 --> 00:15:53.500
JTLeague.com slash talks, they wrote a nice little

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:55.500
article about us. And then

00:15:55.500 --> 00:15:57.500
if you want to get involved, we would love for you

00:15:57.500 --> 00:15:59.500
to reach out to us about being a mentor,

00:15:59.500 --> 00:16:01.500
hiring a graduate of our program, becoming

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:03.500
a customer of our company, or donating

00:16:03.500 --> 00:16:05.500
to help us train more people in data

00:16:05.500 --> 00:16:07.500
science. And thank you very much for your attention.

00:16:07.500 --> 00:16:09.500
Applause

00:16:09.500 --> 00:16:11.500
Applause

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:13.500
Applause

00:16:13.500 --> 00:16:15.500
Applause

00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:17.500
Applause

00:16:17.500 --> 00:16:19.500
Applause

00:16:19.500 --> 00:16:21.500
Okay, so having set a new RStudio conf record

00:16:21.500 --> 00:16:23.500
for syllables per second. Yes!

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:25.500
First question that comes

00:16:25.500 --> 00:16:27.500
up, where can people

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:29.500
get training in all the stuff

00:16:29.500 --> 00:16:31.500
you had to learn that wasn't data science?

00:16:31.500 --> 00:16:33.500
You mentioned HR. I imagine there's a whole

00:16:33.500 --> 00:16:35.500
bunch of other things you had to learn. To run this project?

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:37.500
To do things like this.

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:39.500
That's a good question.

00:16:39.500 --> 00:16:41.500
I'm not sure I'd recommend

00:16:41.500 --> 00:16:43.500
that someone go and try to learn all those things.

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:45.500
What it is, is, you know,

00:16:45.500 --> 00:16:47.500
it's this, the reason why we call the company Problem Forward

00:16:47.500 --> 00:16:49.500
is because we think about problem forward, not

00:16:49.500 --> 00:16:51.500
solution backward. We're trying to figure out what's the problem

00:16:51.500 --> 00:16:53.500
and then solve the barriers instead of

00:16:53.500 --> 00:16:55.500
ending up with a solution and reverse engineering it.

00:16:55.500 --> 00:16:57.500
And what I found in not only

00:16:57.500 --> 00:16:59.500
this project, but every project is,

00:16:59.500 --> 00:17:01.500
if you pick a project, an end point

00:17:01.500 --> 00:17:03.500
or a project you really care about, a problem you really

00:17:03.500 --> 00:17:05.500
care about, you just have to learn

00:17:05.500 --> 00:17:07.500
a whole bunch of stuff that is unrelated.

00:17:07.500 --> 00:17:09.500
You wish it would just be R scripting, but it never is.

00:17:09.500 --> 00:17:11.500
Okay. Next question.

00:17:11.500 --> 00:17:13.500
How has all of this

00:17:13.500 --> 00:17:15.500
changed what

00:17:15.500 --> 00:17:17.500
you teach and how you teach at the university?

00:17:17.500 --> 00:17:19.500
Yeah, so the online

00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:21.500
courses were actually,

00:17:21.500 --> 00:17:23.500
I've been teaching this advanced data science course

00:17:23.500 --> 00:17:25.500
at Johns Hopkins for years

00:17:25.500 --> 00:17:27.500
using R and RStudio and stuff like that

00:17:27.500 --> 00:17:29.500
before Coursera.

00:17:29.500 --> 00:17:31.500
Then we did Coursera and now we've been,

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:33.500
Coursera and online programs

00:17:33.500 --> 00:17:35.500
like LeanPub and Coursera have been kind of our

00:17:35.500 --> 00:17:37.500
like, it's like our education labs.

00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:39.500
We like run it there first, try it out,

00:17:39.500 --> 00:17:41.500
see how it works, learn all the

00:17:41.500 --> 00:17:43.500
things that go wrong when a thousand people try to

00:17:43.500 --> 00:17:45.500
learn it that way and then kind of build it back

00:17:45.500 --> 00:17:47.500
into our local in-person program.

00:17:47.500 --> 00:17:49.500
It's kind of a cool, yeah, way to do that.

00:17:49.500 --> 00:17:51.500
Okay, and one last question

00:17:51.500 --> 00:17:53.500
and this one's from me.

00:17:53.500 --> 00:17:55.500
If you could send email back in time

00:17:55.500 --> 00:17:57.500
to the day you first thought of doing this,

00:17:57.500 --> 00:17:59.500
what would you tell yourself?

00:17:59.500 --> 00:18:01.500
So many things, but I think the first thing

00:18:01.500 --> 00:18:03.500
that I would say is be super

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:05.500
grateful to all of the people that took

00:18:05.500 --> 00:18:07.500
the gamble with you on this. Like I said, a lot of people

00:18:07.500 --> 00:18:09.500
kind of gambled with their careers to help me do this

00:18:09.500 --> 00:18:11.500
and I deeply appreciate that.

00:18:11.500 --> 00:18:13.500
And then the second thing I think I would have said,

00:18:13.500 --> 00:18:15.500
and this is a true story, is JJ

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:17.500
talked about creating an economic engine that allows him

00:18:17.500 --> 00:18:19.500
to do other things first and I didn't

00:18:19.500 --> 00:18:21.500
generate the economic engine first and that

00:18:21.500 --> 00:18:23.500
has been challenging. I wish I had done

00:18:23.500 --> 00:18:25.500
economic engine first, social mission

00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:27.500
second, but, you know,

00:18:27.500 --> 00:18:29.500
it's still working out.

00:18:29.500 --> 00:18:31.500
I'm not sure that's a hard and fast thing, but it's

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:33.500
a nice idea. So, thanks.

00:18:33.500 --> 00:18:35.500
All right, one more round of applause, please, for Jeff and his program.

00:18:35.500 --> 00:18:37.500
Thank you, everybody.

